Seq[Any](format.raw/*1.1*/("""<div>

  <h2>Dictonary meaning</h2>
  <p>
    <b>Kerkovi</b> is a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kurdish_languages" target="_blank"><i>Kurdish</i>
  </a> word that stands for

    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zebra" target="_blank">
      <i>Zebra</i></a>

    .
  </p>

  <img src="/img/zebra.jpg" style="float : right" class="gomulu" height="200" >
  <p>
    It stems from two words joined: Ker + kovi.</p>
  <p>
    <i><b>Ker</b></i> means <b><i>donkey</i></b> and <b><i>kovi</i></b> means <b><i>wild</i></b>.
    <br/>Therefore, <b><i>kerkovi</i></b> means <b><i>Wild donkey</i></b>.
  </p>
  <p>It does not have a common usage in the language. I have heard my parents use it in
    the

    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northern_Kurdish" target="_blank"><i>Kurmanji</i></a> dialect. Since there is no information
    about the word on the internet, I don't know whether it is also used in other
    dialects such as

    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zaza_language" target="_blank"><i>Zazaki</i></a> and
    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_Kurdish" target="_blank"><i>Sorani</i></a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The word popularly used is <i>'Zebra'</i>,
    and too few people know this beautiful word. Now you are one of them :)
  </p>



